descriptive_long.question:
Prove that for every positive integer $targetnum$, there is a sequence of integers $startzero, firstval, \dots, finalval$ with $startzero = 0$ and $finalval = targetnum$ such that each term after $startzero$ is either an earlier term plus $2^{powindex}$ for some nonnegative integer $powindex$, or of the form $bigexpon\,\mathrm{mod}\,modconst$ for some earlier positive terms $bigexpon$ and $modconst$. [Here $bigexpon\,\mathrm{mod}\,modconst$ denotes the remainder when $bigexpon$ is divided by $modconst$, so $0 \leq (bigexpon\,\mathrm{mod}\,modconst) < modconst$.]

\end{itemize}

